Here's the model, locked and ready to code against. I'd keep this dead simple — in-memory JS objects or a single Firebase/Supabase collection, no relational DB setup needed for a hackathon.

typescript
// ---- Student ----
type Profile = "dyslexia" | "adhd" | "blind" | "deaf" | "low_vision";

interface Student {
  id: string;          // "aisha", "tom", "sam" — just use names as IDs, keep it simple
  name: string;
  profile: Profile;    // one primary tag per student for the demo
}

// ---- Lesson ----
interface Slide {
  index: number;
  content_text: string;   // title + body, plain text
  image_alt?: string;     // optional, for TTS to read if slide has an image
}

interface Lesson {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  slides: Slide[];
  current_slide_index: number;   // updated live, broadcast to students
  live_transcript: string;       // append-only, grows during class
  live_summary: string;          // regenerated periodically from transcript
}

// ---- Homework ----
interface Homework {
  id: string;
  lesson_id: string;                          // links back to the Lesson for grounding
  raw_content: string;                        // pasted text (skip PDF parsing unless time allows)
  student_versions: Record<string, string>;   // student.id -> transformed content
}
A few decisions baked in here that you should all agree on before splitting off:

IDs are just strings (names), no UUIDs. Don't waste time on ID generation logic for a 3-4 student demo.
One profile per student, not a list. Keeps every prompt/transform simple — no need to merge multiple accommodation rules.
live_transcript and live_summary live directly on Lesson, not a separate table — Person 2 just appends/updates one object.
Homework.lesson_id is the single link that makes 3.5 possible — Person 3 must not skip wiring this up, even for the demo, or the grounded Q&A has nothing to pull context from.
No PDF handling in the model — raw_content is plain text. If someone wants PDF upload, extract text first, but that's a stretch, not part of the core model.
Storage decision needed now: in-memory (single JS object/array in a server process, resets on refresh — fastest, zero setup, fine for a live demo) vs. Firebase/Supabase (survives refresh, slightly more setup, useful if the teacher and student views run in separate browser tabs/devices and need to sync through a real backend rather than local state).

Given you have live sync (teacher slide → student view) across what's likely two different screens/laptops in the demo, you probably need some shared backend — even Firebase Realtime Database or a simple WebSocket server on Express holding this object in memory would work. Which do you want to commit to, so Person 1's sync work and Person 3's homework linkage are both built against the same source of truth?







